An optimized approach is Brian Kernighan's Algorithm. Instead of shifting and checking every bit one by one (which always runs 32 loops), this algorithm clears the lowest set bit in each iteration using the expression 'v & (v - 1)'. This means the loop only runs as many times as there are actual set bits in the integer.

```c
#include <stdint.h>

int count_set_bits(uint32_t v) {
    int count = 0;
    while (v) {
        v &= (v - 1); // clears the lowest set bit
        count++;
    }
    return count;
}
```

You can reverse the bits of a 32-bit integer efficiently by swapping adjacent blocks of bits in memory using a series of masks and shifts, similar to a binary merge sort. We swap adjacent single bits, then adjacent 2-bit groups, then 4-bit, 8-bit, and finally 16-bit halves.

```c
#include <stdint.h>

uint32_t reverse_bits(uint32_t n) {
    n = ((n >> 1) & 0x55555555) | ((n & 0x55555555) << 1);
    n = ((n >> 2) & 0x33333333) | ((n & 0x33333333) << 2);
    n = ((n >> 4) & 0x0F0F0F0F) | ((n & 0x0F0F0F0F) << 4);
    n = ((n >> 8) & 0x00FF00FF) | ((n & 0x00FF00FF) << 8);
    n = ( n >> 16)             | ( n             << 16);
    return n;
}
```

In C, the equality comparison operator '==' has a higher precedence than the bitwise AND operator '&'. Because of this, the compiler processes the expression 'if (x & 1 == 0)' as 'if (x & (1 == 0))', which simplifies to 'if (x & 0)', evaluating to false (0) regardless of the value of x. To correct this, you must wrap the bitwise operation in parentheses to force it to evaluate first:

```c
if ((x & 1) == 0) {
    /* Executes correctly if the lowest bit of x is zero */
}
```

You can swap two integers using three XOR operations in a row. This works because XOR is its own inverse.

```c
void xor_swap(int *x, int *y) {
    if (x == y) return; /* Critical safety check */
    *x ^= *y;
    *y ^= *x;
    *x ^= *y;
}
```

The primary risk is when 'x' and 'y' point to the exact same memory address (aliasing). If 'x == y', the first line '*x ^= *y' evaluates to '*x ^= *x', which clears the variable to 0. Without the safety check, the function will zero out the value instead of swapping it.

A non-zero number is a power of two if it has exactly one bit set to 1 in its binary representation. You can check this in O(1) constant time by evaluating the expression 'x & (x - 1)'. If 'x' is a power of two, subtracting 1 flips all bits below the single set bit, and performing an AND operation of this with 'x' yields 0. We must also verify that 'x' is not 0.

```c
#include <stdbool.h>
#include <stdint.h>

bool is_power_of_two(uint32_t x) {
    return (x != 0) && ((x & (x - 1)) == 0);
}
```

